  <h2>Understanding Sonoma Wine</h2>
  <p>When it comes to sonoma wine, quality matters more than price. Our team of sommeliers has tasted hundreds of options to bring you these expert recommendations.</p>

<h2>History & Origins of Sonoma Wine</h2>

<p>Sonoma County's winemaking legacy began in 1812 when Russian settlers at Fort Ross planted the first commercial vineyards along California's North Coast. However, the region's true viticultural foundation was established by Hungarian nobleman <strong>Agoston Haraszthy</strong>, known as the "Father of California Viticulture," who founded Buena Vista Winery in 1857 and imported over 100,000 European vine cuttings, fundamentally transforming Sonoma's grape growing potential.</p>

<p>The late 19th century marked Sonoma's golden age, with Italian immigrant families like the Sebastianis (1904) and Foppiano (1896) establishing generational wineries that remain cornerstones of the region today. The <strong>Kunde family</strong> began farming in 1904, while <strong>Gundlach Bundschu</strong>, California's oldest continuously family-owned winery, survived both the 1906 San Francisco earthquake and Prohibition by selling grapes to home winemakers.</p>

<p>Prohibition (1920-1933) devastated Sonoma's wine industry, with many vineyards converted to prune orchards or abandoned entirely. The region's renaissance began in the 1960s when pioneering vintners like <strong>Joe Swan</strong> and <strong>Tom Dehlinger</strong> recognized Sonoma's exceptional terroir for Pinot Noir and Chardonnay, particularly in the cool Russian River Valley.</p>

<h3>Modern Recognition and Classification</h3>

<p>The establishment of <strong>Russian River Valley AVA</strong> in 1983 marked Sonoma's entry into formal wine region classification, followed by Sonoma Coast AVA (1987) and Alexander Valley AVA (1984). Today, Sonoma County encompasses 18 distinct American Viticultural Areas, each with unique microclimates and soil compositions.</p>

<p>The region gained international acclaim in the 1970s and 1980s as quality-focused producers like <strong>Williams Selyem</strong>, <strong>Kosta Browne</strong>, and <strong>Rochioli</strong> demonstrated that Sonoma's diverse terroir could produce world-class wines rivaling Burgundy and Bordeaux. Modern Sonoma represents over 60,000 acres of vineyards across 425 wineries, with sustainable farming practices and innovative winemaking techniques cementing its reputation as one of California's premier wine regions.</p>

<h2>Terroir & Climate</h2>

<h3>Climate Dynamics</h3>
<p>Sonoma County's complex climate is defined by its proximity to the Pacific Ocean and the dramatic interplay between coastal fog and inland heat. The region experiences a <strong>Mediterranean climate</strong> with warm, dry summers averaging 75-85°F during the day, dropping to 45-55°F at night—a diurnal temperature swing crucial for maintaining acidity in grapes. Annual rainfall ranges from 25-45 inches, concentrated in winter months, while growing season sunshine averages 2,800 hours annually. Vintage variation is significant: cooler years like 2010 and 2011 produced wines with bright acidity and elegant structure, while warmer vintages such as 2014 and 2015 yielded more concentrated, powerful expressions.</p>

<h3>Diverse Soil Composition</h3>
<p>Sonoma's geological complexity stems from tectonic activity and ancient seabeds. <strong>Goldridge soils</strong> dominate the western regions, offering excellent drainage through sandy loam that stresses vines beneficially, concentrating flavors in Pinot Noir and Chardonnay. The Mayacamas Mountains contribute <strong>volcanic ash and red clay</strong>, particularly around Glen Ellen and Kenwood, imparting mineral complexity and firm tannin structure to Cabernet Sauvignon. <strong>Franciscan shale and sandstone</strong> in areas like Dry Creek Valley provide good water retention, supporting the herbaceous complexity found in exceptional Sauvignon Blanc. Alluvial gravel deposits along creek beds, especially in Alexander Valley, create well-draining conditions that produce Cabernet Sauvignon with cassis intensity and graphite minerality.</p>

<h3>Geographic Influence</h3>
<p>Elevations range from sea level along the Sonoma Coast to 2,663 feet atop Mount St. Helena. <strong>Hillside vineyards</strong> between 400-1,200 feet, such as those on Sonoma Mountain, benefit from superior drainage and sun exposure, yielding wines with concentrated fruit and structured tannins. South-facing slopes capture maximum solar radiation, while north-facing sites remain cooler, preserving acidity. Key geographic zones include the fog-cooled <strong>Petaluma Gap</strong>, where Chardonnay develops citrus precision and mineral tension, and the warmer <strong>Knights Valley</strong>, where Cabernet Sauvignon achieves full phenolic ripeness while retaining freshness.</p>

<h3>Microclimate Factors</h3>
<p>The <strong>Russian River</strong> acts as a fog conduit, channeling marine air inland through the Petaluma Gap, creating cooling effects that extend 15-20 miles from the coast. This fog burn-off pattern creates distinct microclimates: vineyards closer to the river experience cooler conditions producing wines with bright red fruit and earthy undertones, while sites just miles away develop richer, darker fruit characteristics. The <strong>Mayacamas and Sonoma Mountains</strong> create rain shadows and thermal protection, allowing extended hang time that develops complex secondary flavors—leather, tobacco, and dried herbs—particularly evident in premium Cabernet Sauvignon from Bennett Valley and Sonoma Valley floor sites.</p>

<h2>What Does Sonoma Wine Taste Like?</h2>

<div class="bg-wine-50 p-6 rounded-lg mb-6">
<p>Sonoma County's diverse microclimates and soil types create wines with remarkable complexity and terroir expression. From the fog-kissed Pinot Noirs of the Russian River Valley to the powerful Cabernets of Alexander Valley, each bottle tells the story of its specific vineyard site.</p>
